#compdef frink
# =============================================================================
# frink — Alan Eliasen's "Frink" — a calculating tool and
#         programming language with BUILT-IN AWARENESS OF
#         PHYSICAL UNITS.  Every numeric value in Frink can
#         carry a dimensional unit (meter, kilogram, second,
#         tesla, candela, hectare, fortnight); the language
#         tracks units through every operation and raises
#         dimensional-analysis errors when units don't match.
#         Frink ships with a 4500+ line "units file" defining
#         physical constants, SI/imperial/historical/regional
#         units, scientific conversions, and even astronomical
#         data.  Implemented in Java; distributed as
#         frink.jar from frinklang.org.
#         Distinguishing from GNU units (POSIX units converter),
#         Wolfram Alpha (web calculator), Maxima / Mathematica
#         (computer algebra), and other unit-aware tools by:
#           - UNITS AS FIRST-CLASS VALUES — `78 yards -> feet`
#             evaluates to `234.0 [feet]`; you can assign
#             unit-bearing values to variables and pass them
#             through operations:
#               speed = 60 miles/hour
#               distance = speed * 2 hours
#               // distance: 120 [miles]
#               distance -> km
#               // 193.121280 [km]
#           - DIMENSIONAL ANALYSIS at runtime — adding meters
#             and kilograms raises an error:
#               1 meter + 1 kilogram
#               // Error: Cannot add quantities of incompatible
#               // dimensions
#           - ARBITRARY-PRECISION RATIONAL NUMBERS — Frink
#             stores numbers as exact rationals by default,
#             avoiding floating-point rounding:
#               1/3 + 1/3 + 1/3
#               // 1 (not 0.9999999...)
#               (1/3)^100
#               // 1/515377520732011331036461129765621272702107522001
#           - 4500+ UNIT DEFINITIONS shipped with the standard
#             units file (override with -u or disable with
#             --nounits):
#               SI units: m / kg / s / A / K / mol / cd
#               Imperial: foot / pound / mile / acre / gallon
#               Astronomical: parsec / lightyear / AU
#               Historical: cubit / furlong / fortnight
#               Regional: tan (Japan) / li (China) / dunam (Israel)
#               Scientific: tesla / weber / coulomb / dyne / erg
#           - INTERVAL ARITHMETIC — uncertainty propagation:
#               (10±0.1) meters * (20±0.2) meters
#               // 200 [meter^2] (uncertainty: 4)
#           - 4 EXECUTION MODES via flags:
#               * GUI MODES   — --swing / --gui (Swing GUI),
#                              --awt (AWT GUI), --fullscreen
#                              (fullscreen), -1 / -3 (Swing
#                              one-line / multi-line)
#               * --prog       — blank programming-mode window
#               * -open FILE   — start editing FILE
#               * (default)    — command-line REPL or script
#                              execution
#           - SANDBOX MODE via --sandbox — restrict file +
#             network access for untrusted scripts
#           - INTEGRATED HELP via `help` keyword inside Frink
#             session
#           - CUSTOM UNITS FILE via -u FILE — replace the
#             default 4500+ definitions with a custom set
#           - NO UNITS via --nounits / -nu — pure-numeric mode
#             without the units file (saves startup time for
#             non-physics scripts)
#           - -e "EXPR" — one-shot expression evaluation
#             ideal for shell scripting:
#               $ java -cp frink.jar frink.parser.Frink -e "1 light-year -> km"
#               9.4607304725808e12 [km]
#           - SOLAR / ASTRONOMICAL CALCULATIONS — built-in
#             astronomical functions: sunrise, sunset, moon
#             phases, planetary positions
#           - GRAPHEME-AWARE STRING OPS — wordList, sentenceList,
#             lineBreakList all respect Unicode locale rules
#           - JAVA INTEROP — `newJava[]` constructor calls Java
#             classes directly; Frink as Java scripting glue
#         Used by: physics + engineering homework / production
#         calculations, "what's the speed of an unladen
#         swallow?" trivia (Frink famously can compute it),
#         astronomy + space mission analysis, conversion-heavy
#         data analysis (Imperial ↔ SI cleanup, currency-as-
#         unit), and as the canonical example of a programming
#         language designed with dimensional analysis as a
#         core abstraction.
#
# Author:  Alan Eliasen (futureboy.us, frinklang.org) — Colorado-
#          based software engineer + physics enthusiast.
#          Created Frink in 1994; sole maintainer since then.
#          License: Custom restrictive (free for personal/
#          educational use; contact author for commercial).
# Source:  https://frinklang.org/ (official site + docs)
#          https://frinklang.org/frinkjar/frink.jar (binary)
#          Source code is closed (not published to GitHub);
#          documentation is the canonical reference.
# Manpage: No manpage; documentation lives at
#          https://frinklang.org/ (Frink Web Site).
# Language: Frink (https://frinklang.org/).  Distinct from:
#              * GNU units (POSIX standalone units converter,
#                no general-purpose programming)
#              * Wolfram Alpha (web-based; closed; not a
#                programming language)
#              * Mathematica (broader algebra system; no
#                runtime dimensional checks by default)
#              * Maxima (computer algebra; no first-class units)
#              * F# Units of Measure (compile-time only; F#-
#                specific)
#              * Boost.Units (C++ template metaprogramming;
#                compile-time)
#              * Haskell's dimensional package (compile-time)
#           Frink distinguishes itself by:
#              1. UNITS AS RUNTIME VALUES — every numeric value
#                 carries a unit; operations check dimensions
#                 at runtime
#              2. ARBITRARY-PRECISION RATIONALS — exact
#                 arithmetic; no IEEE floating-point surprises
#              3. INTERVAL ARITHMETIC — uncertainty
#                 propagation through calculations
#              4. ALAN-ELIASEN SOLO MAINTENANCE — sole
#                 developer since 1994
#              5. JAVA RUNTIME — JVM portability + Java
#                 interop
#              6. 4500+ UNIT DEFINITIONS — most comprehensive
#                 units library in any single language
#              7. ASTRONOMICAL FUNCTIONS — sunrise / moon
#                 phase / planetary positions built-in
#              8. GRAPHEME-AWARE STRINGS — Unicode-correct
#                 string operations
#              9. SANDBOX MODE — restricted file + network
#                 access for untrusted scripts
#             10. CLI + GUI + WEB EMBEDDING — single jar
#                 runs as REPL, script interpreter, Swing
#                 GUI, AWT GUI, or applet
# License: Custom restrictive (free personal/educational use)
# Status:  Active since 1994; current version updated
#          regularly on frinklang.org; published as a single
#          frink.jar download; documentation at
#          https://frinklang.org/ is the canonical reference.
#
