#
# WHY FRINK IS A DISTINCTIVE 99TH LANGUAGE:
#
#   1. UNITS AS FIRST-CLASS VALUES — Frink's defining feature.
#      Every numeric value in Frink carries a dimensional unit;
#      operations propagate units; type errors arise when
#      units mismatch:
#         a := 60 miles/hour
#         b := 2 hours
#         d := a * b      // d = 120 miles
#         d := a + b      // ERROR: incompatible dimensions
#      No other major programming language has dimensional
#      analysis as a built-in runtime feature.  F# Units of
#      Measure is compile-time only.  Boost.Units (C++) and
#      Haskell's dimensional are compile-time template
#      metaprogramming.  Frink does it at runtime — meaning
#      you can construct unit-bearing values dynamically
#      from user input.
#
#   2. ARBITRARY-PRECISION RATIONALS — Frink's default
#      numeric type is the exact rational, not IEEE 754
#      floating-point.  Computations like `(1/3) * 3 == 1`
#      are exactly true.  Distinct from every language that
#      uses doubles as the default (which includes virtually
#      all modern mainstream languages).
#
#   3. INTERVAL ARITHMETIC for uncertainty — Frink natively
#      supports interval values with uncertainty:
#         x := 10±0.5      // 9.5 to 10.5
#         y := 20±0.3      // 19.7 to 20.3
#         z := x + y       // 29.2 to 30.8 (uncertainty 1.6)
#      Used in scientific + engineering calculations where
#      measurement uncertainty must propagate.
#
#   4. 4500+ UNIT DEFINITIONS — Frink's stdlib units file is
#      4500+ lines defining:
#         * SI base + derived units (meter, kilogram,
#                                     second, ampere, kelvin,
#                                     mole, candela, plus all
#                                     derived units)
#         * Imperial (foot, pound, mile, acre, gallon,
#                     pint, ounce, ...)
#         * Astronomical (parsec, lightyear, AU, jupiter
#                          mass, solar radius, ...)
#         * Historical (cubit, league, span, hogshead,
#                       fortnight, lustrum, ...)
#         * Regional (tan/koku for Japan, li/jin/cun for
#                     China, dunam for Israel, vara for
#                     Spain, ...)
#         * Scientific (tesla, weber, coulomb, dyne, erg,
#                       parsec, megaparsec, ...)
#         * Currency (with internet-based exchange rate
#                     lookups in some configurations)
#         * Cooking (cup, teaspoon, tablespoon, dash)
#         * Sports (yard, furlong, marathon distance)
#      Most comprehensive single-language units library
#      in existence.
#
#   5. ASTRONOMICAL FUNCTIONS built-in — sunrise(), sunset(),
#      moonPhase(), planetaryPositions().  Solar / lunar
#      calculations used in agriculture, religious holidays,
#      navigation.  Frink can compute:
#         sunrise[40.0 degrees, -105.0 degrees, today]
#         // Returns sunrise time for Boulder, Colorado today
#
#   6. JAVA INTEROP — Frink runs on JVM; can construct Java
#      objects, call Java methods, subclass Java classes via
#      `newJava[ClassName, args]`.  Effectively a unit-aware
#      scripting language for the Java ecosystem.
#
#   7. ALAN ELIASEN / FUTUREBOY.US SOLO MAINTENANCE — Alan
#      Eliasen has been the sole developer of Frink since 1994.
#      The continuity of vision (units + rationals + intervals
#      + scientific computing) reflects single-author
#      coherence.  Distinct from committee-designed languages
#      (Ada, C++, Java).
#
#   8. SANDBOX MODE — `--sandbox` enables restricted runtime
#      that disables file I/O and network access; intended
#      for executing untrusted Frink scripts (e.g., as a
#      JVM-hosted scripting tier in larger applications).
#
#   9. GRAPHEME-AWARE STRINGS — Unicode-correct string
#      operations: wordList, sentenceList, lineBreakList all
#      respect ICU locale rules.  Lexical compare functions
#      use locale-sensitive collation.  Distinct from most
#      languages which default to byte / code-point
#      operations.
#
#  10. CALCULATING DEMOS — Frink is famous for its example
#      calculations that showcase unit-aware programming.
#      "What's the speed of an unladen swallow in furlongs
#      per fortnight?"  "How many pennies stacked vertically
#      would reach the moon?"  "How long would it take a
#      sloth to climb Mount Everest?"  Each calculation is
#      a one-line Frink expression demonstrating dimensional
#      analysis + automatic unit conversion.
